WordPress powers over 40% of all websites, but running WordPress does not automatically mean your site is optimised for search engines. In fact, the opposite is often true. As a **WordPress SEO consultant**, I work with business owners across the UK — including those searching for a **WordPress SEO consultant Hampshire** or **WordPress SEO consultant Southampton** — to transform underperforming WordPress sites into traffic-generating assets.

I am Sunny Patel, and I have spent years untangling the SEO problems that WordPress sites accumulate over time. From plugin conflicts to bloated themes, I have seen it all — and I know exactly how to fix it.

## Why WordPress Needs Specialist SEO

WordPress is a powerful content management system, but its flexibility is also its weakness. Out of the box, WordPress ships with default settings that actively harm your search visibility. Unchecked permalink structures, auto-generated taxonomy pages, and poorly coded themes all contribute to a site that Google struggles to crawl efficiently.

**Plugin bloat** is one of the most common issues I encounter. Site owners install plugins for every conceivable function — sliders, social sharing, contact forms, caching, analytics — and each one adds weight. Every plugin loads its own CSS and JavaScript files, many of which fire on every single page regardless of whether they are needed. The result is a slow, render-blocked site that fails Core Web Vitals and frustrates visitors.

**Theme issues** compound the problem. Many popular WordPress themes are built to look impressive in demos but ship with enormous amounts of unused code. They load font libraries, icon sets, and animation scripts globally, creating page weights that would make any performance engineer wince. A theme that scores well in a demo environment often crumbles under real-world conditions with actual content and plugins installed.

Then there are the **default settings** that most site owners never change. WordPress generates tag pages, author archives, date archives, and media attachment pages by default. Each of these creates thin, duplicate content that dilutes your crawl budget and confuses search engines about which pages matter most.

## Common WordPress SEO Problems I Fix

Over hundreds of WordPress audits, I have identified the issues that appear most frequently — and cause the most damage.

**Slow page speed from plugins** tops the list. I regularly audit sites running 30 or more plugins when 12 would suffice. Each redundant plugin is dead weight. I identify which plugins are essential, which can be replaced with lightweight alternatives, and which should be removed entirely.

**Poor permalink structure** is surprisingly common. Sites running default permalinks (the ?p=123 format) or overly complex URL structures with dates and categories baked in are leaving rankings on the table. I restructure URLs to be clean, keyword-relevant, and flat — then handle redirects so you do not lose any existing authority.

**Thin taxonomy pages** — tags, categories, and custom taxonomies — often index hundreds of near-empty pages. These waste crawl budget and create duplicate content signals. I audit every taxonomy, noindex or consolidate where appropriate, and ensure the ones that remain are genuinely useful to both users and search engines.

**Missing schema markup** is another gap I frequently close. WordPress does not output structured data by default, and many themes only add the most basic schema if any at all. I implement custom schema — FAQ, HowTo, LocalBusiness, Article, Product — to give your pages the best chance of earning rich results.

**Render-blocking resources** slow down your Largest Contentful Paint and hurt your Core Web Vitals scores. I defer non-critical JavaScript, inline critical CSS, and ensure your above-the-fold content loads as quickly as physically possible.

**Poor mobile performance** rounds out the usual suspects. With Google's mobile-first indexing, a WordPress site that only works well on desktop is a site that will not rank. I test across devices and fix layout shifts, tap target issues, and viewport problems that harm your mobile experience.

If any of these sound familiar, a [technical SEO audit](/services/technical-seo-audit) is the logical starting point.

## WordPress SEO Services

My WordPress SEO consultancy covers every aspect of optimising your WP site for organic search.

### Yoast and Rank Math Configuration

Most site owners install Yoast or Rank Math and assume the job is done. It is not. These plugins are powerful, but they require proper configuration. I set up XML sitemaps correctly, configure canonical URLs, manage crawl directives for taxonomies and archives, and ensure your meta titles and descriptions follow best practices for [on-page SEO](/services/on-page-seo).

### Core Web Vitals Optimisation

Google uses Core Web Vitals as a ranking signal, and WordPress sites are particularly prone to failing these metrics. I optimise your Largest Contentful Paint, First Input Delay, and Cumulative Layout Shift through image compression, lazy loading, script deferral, font optimisation, and server-side caching configuration.

### Custom Schema Implementation

I go beyond what SEO plugins offer and implement custom structured data tailored to your content type and business. Whether you need FAQ schema for your service pages, Product schema for your WooCommerce store, or LocalBusiness schema for your location pages, I build it properly and validate it against Google's requirements.

### Content Strategy and Architecture

Rankings are not just about technical fixes. I help you build a content architecture that supports topical authority — proper category structures, strategic [internal linking](/services/internal-linking), content hubs, and a publishing calendar focused on the keywords that will actually drive revenue.

### WooCommerce SEO

If you are running WooCommerce, your WordPress SEO needs extend into product optimisation, category page strategy, and handling the duplicate content issues that WooCommerce generates by default. My WooCommerce work overlaps with my [ecommerce SEO consultant](/services/ecommerce-seo-consultant) service, so you get the benefit of deep ecommerce expertise applied specifically to the WordPress ecosystem.

